To add custom tables to the auto-generated database in an ASP.NET Core MVC .NET 6 project, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a class representing your custom table (referred to as a model).

```csharp
public class CustomTable
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
}
```

2. In your `DbContext` class (e.g., ApplicationDbContext), add a `DbSet<T>` property for your custom table:

```csharp
public class ApplicationDbContext : IdentityDbContext
{
    public ApplicationDbContext(DbContextOptions<ApplicationDbContext> options)
        : base(options)
    {
    }

    public DbSet<CustomTable> CustomTables { get; set; }
}
```

3. Create a migration for the custom table:

```bash
dotnet ef migrations add AddCustomTable --context ApplicationDbContext
```

4. Update the database to apply the migration:

```bash
dotnet ef database update --context ApplicationDbContext
```

That's it! Now, the custom table will be added to your auto-generated database. To make use of this table for CRUD operations, you can create a controller and views when using MVC.

Here's a simple example of how to create a controller for the custom table:

1. Right-click on Controllers folder, select Add -> Controller.
2. In the "Add New Scaffolded Item" window, select MVC Controller with views, using Entity Framework and click "Add".
3. In the "Add MVC Controller with views, using Entity Framework" window, select your Model class (e.g., CustomTable) and Data context class (e.g., ApplicationDbContext). You can also change the controller name. Click "Add".

Now you'll have a controller and views for managing the custom table, performing Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD) operations.

To make a smooth scroll transition to each section when the navigation links are clicked, you can add a simple JavaScript snippet at the end of the HTML file. I've modified the example below to include the smooth scroll transition:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="ar" dir="rtl">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <link href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/tailwindcss@2.2.19/dist/tailwind.min.css" rel="stylesheet">
  <title>خدمات الصيانة</title>
  <meta name="description" content="خدمات الصيانة الجيدة لعمال البناء.">
  <meta itemprop="keywords" content="صيانة, بناء, خدمات">
</head>
<body class="bg-gray-100">
  <!-- The rest of the HTML content goes here -->

  <script>
    document.querySelectorAll('a[href^="#"]').forEach(anchor => {
      anchor.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
        e.preventDefault();

        document.querySelector(this.getAttribute('href')).scrollIntoView({
          behavior: 'smooth'
        });
      });
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

The `<script>` element at the end will add a smooth scrolling effect to all the navigation links that navigate to the sections within the same page. When you click on the links, the page will smoothly scroll to the target sections.

Here is an HTML and JavaScript code snippet to create a typing carousel effect without using any external libraries:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Typing Carousel</title>
  <style>
    .typing-carousel {
      font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
      font-size: 24px;
      height: 1.5em;
      position: relative;
      overflow: hidden;
    }

    .typing-carousel span {
      position: absolute;
      white-space: nowrap;
      opacity: 0;
    }

    .typing-carousel span.active {
      opacity: 1;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="typing-carousel">
    <span>Carousel text 1</span>
    <span>Carousel text 2</span>
    <span>Carousel text 3</span>
  </div>

  <script>
    const carouselItems = document.querySelectorAll('.typing-carousel span');
    let currentItem = 0;
    let currentItemChar = 0;

    function typeCarouselText() {
      if (currentItemChar < carouselItems[currentItem].textContent.length) {
        carouselItems[currentItem].textContent = carouselItems[currentItem].textContent.slice(
          0,
          currentItemChar + 1
        );

        currentItemChar++;
        setTimeout(typeCarouselText, 100); // Delay between characters typing
      } else {
        currentItemChar = 0;
        setTimeout(() => {
          carouselItems[currentItem].classList.remove('active');
          currentItem++;
          if (currentItem >= carouselItems.length) {
            currentItem = 0;
          }
          carouselItems[currentItem].classList.add('active');
          typeCarouselText();
        }, 2000); // Delay between carousel items
      }
    }

    carouselItems[currentItem].classList.add('active');
    typeCarouselText();
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this code, we first style the `.typing-carousel` element to hide the overflow and position the text within it. Then, we have a JavaScript function `typeCarouselText` that types the text character by character with a specified delay between characters, and when it's done typing, it slides to the next text and repeats the process.

You can adjust the delays (given in milliseconds) between characters typing and between carousel items by changing the values in the `setTimeout` functions in the JavaScript code.

Apologies for the oversight in the code snippet. Let's try another approach that should work better.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Typing Carousel</title>
  <style>
    .typing-carousel {
      font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
      font-size: 24px;
      position: relative;
      min-height: 1.5em;
    }

    .typing-carousel span {
      position: absolute;
      white-space: nowrap;
      display: none;
    }

    .typing-carousel span.active {
      display: inline;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="typing-carousel">
    <span>Carousel text 1</span>
    <span>Carousel text 2</span>
    <span>Carousel text 3</span>
  </div>

  <script>
    const carouselItems = document.querySelectorAll('.typing-carousel span');
    let currentItem = 0;
    let currentItemChar = -1;
    let originalTexts = [];

    carouselItems.forEach(item => originalTexts.push(item.textContent));

    function typeCarouselText() {
      if (currentItemChar < originalTexts[currentItem].length - 1) {
        currentItemChar++;
        carouselItems[currentItem].textContent = originalTexts[currentItem].slice(0, currentItemChar + 1);
        setTimeout(typeCarouselText, 100); // Delay between characters typing
      } else {
        currentItemChar = -1;
        setTimeout(() => {
          carouselItems[currentItem].classList.remove('active');
          currentItem++;
          if (currentItem >= carouselItems.length) {
            currentItem = 0;
          }
          carouselItems[currentItem].classList.add('active');
          typeCarouselText();
        }, 2000); // Delay between carousel items
      }
    }

    carouselItems[currentItem].classList.add('active');
    carouselItems[currentItem].style.display = 'inline';
    typeCarouselText();
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

Here's what I've changed in the code:

1. The original `opacity` and `overflow:hidden` styles were replaced with `display: none` and `display: inline`.
2. I initialized `currentItemChar` with `-1` instead of `0` to add the text char by char, starting with the first character.
3. I added a variable `originalTexts` containing the original texts from the carousel items to avoid repeated appending of the same text.

Now the HTML page should display the carousel items one by one, with a typing effect.

